{"author":{"id":"30a9cdd9e5369167dc36be4d3e5f98e516aa30b7571a17013bc815eef45f09c3"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1448817239,"nonce":"8yZEOVCEwafVOnGEC8Yq8XcrBH8=","metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDE2MDQzMjY3Mw==","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/425#issuecomment-160432673"},"message":"@bgruening I've been doing spot checks on the packages I've been adding to the CPC, \"does this look like it is supposed to\". By `check.py` which script are you referring to?\n\n\u003e For me the checksum is more to prevent other attacks after the initial upload or during download.\n\nyep. and to spot changed packages/have them \"break\" during install in a clearer + safer ways (i.e. we're not trying to run python on an HTML 404 page instead of the python script we intended to download)\n\n@martenson \n\n\u003e I would prefer to not spend Galaxy's time - or IUC's - to go through every revision of every TS package/recipe and manually check the downloadables that are being fetched. \n\nI'm not suggesting that. I'm just actually looking at the things that are added to the CPC to make sure they look like what they're supposed to. I'm basically done adding sha256s to tools-iuc, tools-devteam will be very easy to do after this since most of that stuff is already in the CPC.\n\n\u003e If you try to be perfect you would have to probably do an audit of the whole source to make sure it is not malicious.\n\nYeah, that's just not possible to do, and not what I'm trying to accomplish here. I'm making a best-effort attempt to say \"this downloadable looks like what the author probably intended to be downloaded\" when adding to the CPC (and by extension, all of the IUC's packages).\n\n\u003e It is great way onward - to check every new package - but I am afraid the choice here is whether to add automatic checksums for past software or not do anything.\n\nSo are you suggesting that you wish to modify ALL packages to automatically insert a checksum if it is missing? That seems... aggressive, and was also completely unclear from the original post. That's a very different idea and one I'm definitely more open to.","files":null}]}